\f0\fs28 \cf2 specific objectives of the preservation}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 Thibodeau\'92s 4 criteria for choosing a method (2002, p15)}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 \'93\'85 neither the source nor the process need be retained in their original state for a future performance to be considered authentic. As long as the essential parts of the performance can be replicated over time, the source and process can be replaced. (Heslop et al. 2002)\'94}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 However, what is \'91authentic\'92 and what is the \'91essential\'92 part of a representation is subjective, even if the methodology for establishing what these might be is not. Although the performance model operates from a perspective in which \'92archivists are not interested in the \'91original\'92 record but in capturing and recreating the fleeting and temporary performance of that record\'92 (Heslop et al. 2002), this is not the only context for preserving digital objects. Although it is true, and has been noted above, that the concept of an \'91original\'92 digital object is questionable, it is still valid to suggest that even if researchers are not as concerned with the \'91original copy\'92 of a digital object in the same way they are interested in the original copy of a paper record, they may still highly value the \'91authenticity\'92 of the original form of a digital object. In which case, although it may be possible to change the \'91process\'92 through which a digital object can be accessed, in this case changing the \'91source\'92 would not be considered an acceptable mechanism for preserving access to that digital object.}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 if it is important to maintain certain parts of the original digital object, then preservation strategies which change the object they are preserving, such as migration, may not be as appropriate as emulation, which can leave the object unchanged. (idem)}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 LotL p7: Additionally, there is also a question of what would constitute an adequate transformation for the digital object. For example, it is certainly possible to \'91migrate\'92 a digital object from one file format to another, and to maintain the information required for one particular presentation of that data. However, the particular presentation that is preserved can only ever be subjectively considered important. Migrating a digital object may make it impossible to reproduce a different presentation of the data, which might be as or more important to a different party.}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 \'93For instance, one institution may decide to normalise a spreadsheet into a PDF, which would retain the cell values but destroy any formula used to calculate them. This would favour a particular presentation of that digital object over the information form of the original. On the other hand, another institution might decide to normalise spreadsheets into ODF, which may lose some formatting but retain the formula used to derive each cell. In this case, being able to retain the information form of the file would be seen as more important.\'94 (idem p. 8)}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 OR + \'93This institution might decide, therefore, to copy the file from the CD\uc0\u8208 ROM to managed storage, migrate the file into a TIFF [ok because only the presentation should be kept]\'94}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 \'93Another institution may want to retain some of the information carried in the original image\'92s metadata, such as the photographer\'92s name or the type of camera used to take the image. In this case, the institution might still decide to convert the image to TIFF and, in addition, decide to plan its preservation actions in such a way that the significant properties of the image, such colour\uc0\u8208 space or image size, or those identified in the work of Hedstrom and Lee (2002), are maintained across preservation actions. This might, for example, mean that the institution must choose a migration format which supports those particular significant properties.\'94 (idem pp. 8-9)}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2  Depending on what aspects of the data are given more importance, or what presentation of the data is considered more appropriate, different mechanisms for preserving the data over time will be more or less suitable (LotL p7)}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 \'93Over time, unless we take some form of mitigating action, it is likely that our access to digital objects will be compromised. As such, there is strong reason to believe that there will be change, be it in the object itself, its access dependencies or even in our ability to understand the information it carries. We must ensure that when this change occurs, it does so in a way that we have planned, and for which the consequences are predictable.\'94 (LotL conclusion)}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 -> \'93For example, the value of a record of a business or legal transaction in digital form is compromised if it cannot be established that it has not been altered in any way\'94. (Harvey p54)}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 The digital object is what it purports to be (Harvey p54)}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 \'93Authenticity is best protected by documentation that maintains the clear identity of the material\'92 (UNESCO, 2003, p.22). For instance, if it can be established that a digital object has always been kept in the custody of an archive in which every change to it has been recorded (such as changes resulting from migration of the bit-stream \'96 the dates at which migration occurred, to which media, and so on), then we can be more secure about its integrity\'94 (UNESCO + Harvey p54)}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 \'93Clifford Lynch has cogently argued, authentication of preserved ob- jects is ultimately a matter of trust.\'94 (Thibodeau 2002 p 14)}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 Representation \uc0\u8800  thoughts. E.g. authenticity Thibodeau 2002 -> Thomas Jefferson thoughts. We can compare his writing style with other documents to know if a document was his, or his handwriting; but he can have copied a book (his handwriting, not his thoughts) or the document can be a redacted version (printed or written by his secretary) therefore the authenticity can be checked by the content and writing style (not his handwriting, but his thoughts)}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 Need for a criterion or benchmark to assess the authenticity of a reconstructed digital object }

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 -> \'93More precisely, the criteria for authenticity depend on the intended use of the object You can only say something is authentic with respect to some standard or criterion or model for what X is.\'94 (Thibodeau 2002 p 14)}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 The object is complete and has not been altered or corrupted (Harvey p54; Ross, 2002, p.7)}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 \'93Authenticity and integrity demand special attention if preserved digital objects are to be trusted and used as evidence or as a source of information. The ease with which digital objects can be altered adds complexity to these require- ments, as do some preservation strategies, such as migration and normalization (see Chapter 8) which \'91involve transformations of the original bitstream\'94 (Harvey p54 + NSF-DELOS Working Group on Digital Archiving and Preservation, 2003, p.6)}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
