\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 All records by definition bear evidence to some degree of their creator\'92s acts and transactions, thoughts and feelings, and all have an original order and context. But that being said, one is not left much further ahead in defining issues of value or importance or significance, or any of the other terms used in appraisal to distinguish what is kept and what is destroyed}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural

\f0\fs28 \cf2 Do not go together (Cook 2000): \'93Going further and expecting them to be consistent or integrated is like comparing apples and Elvis. And yet the confounding of archival and appraisal theory is what sometimes goes on, explicitly and implicitly concerns the value of records, the reasons or principles why some records are judged to be important and thus preserved by archives, and others are judged not to be important and thus destroyed. The inherent nature of records does not help determine which records, of the billions and billions created each day, actually have long-term, enduring, or archival value.\'94}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\cocoartf1265\cocoasubrtf190
{\fonttbl\f0\fnil\fcharset0 National-Book;}
{\colortbl;\red255\green255\blue255;\red255\green248\blue228;}
